        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down. | Bromley. | Kent. S.E.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Dec 8</date>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I am much obliged for your kind letter &amp; Congratulations.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I am very glad to possess your photograph<ref target="#foot.f3"/>   I enclose one of myself made of me by one of my sons, for I have no other.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>I am particularly glad that you have given me the reference to the comptes Rendus”, for the subject referred to interests me in an <hi rend="underline">especial</hi> manner, &amp; I have obtained very few authentic facts.<ref target="#foot.f5"/></p>
<p>I am glad to hear that you are still working on the Cucurbitacæ;<ref target="#foot.f6"/> I have lately quoted extensively from your most interesting papers on this order, in a work which I am preparing on variation.<ref target="#foot.f7"/> I hope soon to send you a paper on Lythrum which I trust may interest you;<ref target="#foot.f8"/></p>
<p>with Sincere thanks &amp; respect | I remain dear Sir | yours faithfully &amp; obliged | Charles Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the relationship between this letter and the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4703.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. V. Naudin, 6 December 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4703.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. V. Naudin, 6 December 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4703.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. V. Naudin, 6 December 1864</ref> and n. 3.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD probably refers to the photograph taken by his son <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1245.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Erasmus Darwin</ref> in April or May 1864 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4502.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from W. E. Darwin, [19 May 1864]</ref> and n. 8, and frontispiece to this volume).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_5811.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Naudin 1864</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4703.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. V. Naudin, 6 December 1864</ref> and n. 5.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4703.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from C. V. Naudin, 6 December 1864</ref> and n. 6.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">Naudin is cited frequently on Cucurbitaceae in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7951.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Variation</hi></ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f8">CD refers to <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_7749.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Three forms of <hi rend="italic">Lythrum salicaria</hi>’</ref>. The paper was published on 12 December 1864 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2782.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">General index to the Journal of the Linnean Society</hi></ref>). Naudin’s name appears on CD’s presentation list for the paper (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol.12, Appendix III).</note>
